However, the account given in the Gospels says that Joseph discovers
that Mary is pregnant (not by him) and rather than denounce her for
fornication and have her stoned to death, as he could have, he
decides to break the engagement quietly. Then an angel appears to him
and tells him to marry Mary anyway.

I'm currently in the midst of an in-depth  course on religion and
theology for lay peopel sponsored by the Episcopal Church, and right
now, we're on the New Testament. The current thinking on this story
among Biblical scholars stems from the fact that the Gospel writers
liked to spice up their accounts with allusions to more ancient
texts, some valid, some not so valid.

I don't know Hebrew, but whether the word in question means &quot;virgin&quot;
or &quot;young woman,&quot; Matthew takes the passage usually quoted as &quot;And a
virgin shall conceive and bear a son...&quot; out of context. If you look
at the original passage from Isaiah, it refers not to an event in the
distant future (about 700 years in the future), but to an event that
is about to happen very shortly.

The New Testament is full of back references like this.

Form criticismly yours,
Karen Sandness

