I am not a Bible scholar and I know nothing of the languages involved, but I
think an extraordinary claim like this requires extraordinary proof.

I think the birth of Jesus Christ to the virgin mother Mary is a central
tenet of Christianity and this supposed miracle of his birth is cited as
proof that Jesus is the prophesied Christ or Savior; this is why he is said
to be the son of God since he was supposedly not born of conception with a
human father.

There are several mentions in the Old Testament of prophesies to the effect
that a virgin mother will give birth to the son of God.

Think about it: why would anyone make, listen to or give credence to a
prophesy claiming that not a virgin but merely a &quot;young woman&quot; would give
birth to Christ? This would be commonplace and not miraculous at all.

As to the meanings of the words used, as translators, we all know that some
words can have different meanings and nuances. The word &quot;virgin&quot; is fairly
clear in its meaning, but the word &quot;maiden&quot; is not. It can refer to a virgin
as in a &quot;maiden voyage&quot; or the &quot;maidenhead&quot; (hymen), but it can also refer
to a young woman.

Perhaps the Hebrew word in question had meanings something like &quot;maiden&quot; but
it was translated with a more specific Greek word meaning &quot;virgin.&quot; Is this
a translation error?

If it were an error, why would no one have noticed it in the 2000+ years
hence? The Bible has to be one of the most closely studied documents ever.

Regards,

Alan Siegrist
Orinda, CA, USA
