I presume that you are referring to the verses added on to the end of Mark?

The Ascension is certainly missing from the early editions of Mark. But the
Ascension is in the earliest versions of the other three Gospels, as well as
in the intro to Acts, and is alluded to in early catechisms quoted by Paul.

The whole topic of how the Christology stories developed in the NT, and also
based on what the early writers thought the OT said (reading from the Greek
Septuagint rather than from the Hebrew), is a fascinating subject that I
could discuss on and on. But this is getting far from Honyaku's mission. So
I will desist.

David Farnsworth

