It might be helpful to remember, though, the importance that was placed
in those times on the fulfilment of every phrophecy in the scriptures,
right down to the smallest detail. This was carried to such an extreme
that in some cases where the original Old Testament text had a disputed
reading, the New Testament story was written to fulfil both readings.
This resulted in some highly convoluted stories like that in Matthew
26-27, where the repentant Judas returns his blood money and the Jewish
priests use the money to buy a &quot;potter's field.&quot; The story is
deliberately written so that both possible readings of the disputed Old
Testament passage (Zech. 11) are covered.

Given that kind of culture, the translation of Heb. almah (not b'tulah)
in the Septuagint into a word that clearly means &quot;virgin&quot; was a very
consequential decision. Maybe it overstates things to say the &quot;virgin
birth&quot; notion was born of a mistranslation, but the decision to
translate it that way certainly sealed the deal for Christianity.

